Exploratory analysis

Regression Analysis

aggregate(mpg~am, data = mtcars, mean)
##   am      mpg
## 1  0 17.14737
## 2  1 24.39231

So far we can see that automatic cars have a lower mpg than manual cars.

Now lets find the variables that are highly correlated with mpg. We will use a step function to run miltiple linear models to build our multiple regression model.

summary(m2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ wt + qsec + am, data = mtcars)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.4811 -1.5555 -0.7257  1.4110  4.6610 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   9.6178     6.9596   1.382 0.177915    
## wt           -3.9165     0.7112  -5.507 6.95e-06 ***
## qsec          1.2259     0.2887   4.247 0.000216 ***
## am            2.9358     1.4109   2.081 0.046716 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 2.459 on 28 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8497, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8336 
## F-statistic: 52.75 on 3 and 28 DF,  p-value: 1.21e-11

From what we can see above wt, qsec, and am produce the best fit model. the adjusted r-squared also tells us that 83% of the variability is explained by the model.

We can now compare the base model with the model produced by our step function

m0 <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)
anova(m0, m2)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: mpg ~ am
## Model 2: mpg ~ wt + qsec + am
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F   Pr(>F)    
## 1     30 720.90                                 
## 2     28 169.29  2    551.61 45.618 1.55e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The results above indicate that there is a significant contribution from wt and qsec to the accuracy of the model.

Residuals

Next we can check the residuals (Appendix fig. 2) #### Summary * residuals vs fitted - Points for most part randomly scattered so conditions seem to be indipendant. * normal Q-Q -e points for the most part lie on the line indicatiing a normal distribution. * Scale-Location - points seem to be scattered normaly around line indication constant variance. * Residuals vs Leverage - From the graph we can see a few outliers

Hypothesis testing

Lastly can perform a t.test do determine if the differences between a automatic or manual transmission are significant.

t.test(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mpg by am
## t = -3.7671, df = 18.332, p-value = 0.001374
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11.280194  -3.209684
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        17.14737        24.39231

from the t test results we can see that the difference between cars with a automatic transmission compared to a manual transmission is significant.

Executive Summary

Based on the analysis conducted in this project we can conclude that cars with a Manual Transmission get 2.9358 more mpg per gallon adjusted for weight and quarter-mile time; a subsequent t-test showed the difference to be statistically significant.
